# OSI Model

The **Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) Model** is a standardized framework used to understand and describe how data is transmitted across a network.

It divides the communication process into seven distinct layers, with each layer performing specific functions. This layered architecture simplifies network design, troubleshooting, and interoperability between devices from different manufacturers.

### Advantages of the OSI Model

* Standardizes network communication
* Simplifies troubleshooting
* Encourages interoperability
* Separates networking functions into manageable layers

---

# OSI Model Layers

The OSI Model consists of **seven layers**, arranged from the user-facing application layer to the physical transmission medium.

| Layer | Name               | Function                                                      |
| ----- | ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| 7     | Application Layer  | Provides network services to end-user applications            |
| 6     | Presentation Layer | Handles data formatting, encryption, and compression          |
| 5     | Session Layer      | Establishes, manages, and terminates communication sessions   |
| 4     | Transport Layer    | Ensures reliable end-to-end data delivery using TCP/UDP       |
| 3     | Network Layer      | Handles logical addressing and routing using IP               |
| 2     | Data Link Layer    | Manages frame transmission and MAC addressing                 |
| 1     | Physical Layer     | Transmits raw bits through cables, fiber, or wireless signals |

### Easy Mnemonic

**Top to Bottom (7 → 1):**

**A**ll **P**eople **S**eem **T**o **N**eed **D**ata **P**rocessing

(Application → Presentation → Session → Transport → Network → Data Link → Physical)

